        <Commentary>
            <ab>Y2.3b <em>sāuuaŋhaēm</em>] Kellens, Geldner. Cf. Y2.18, Y6.2, Y6.19, Y14.3, Y17.2, Y17.19, Y59.2, Y59.29, VrS352, Vrs35.32, G1.6, DrYt4.3. 
                Iranian mss. mostly <em>-īm</em>, but attestations of <em>-aēm</em> in some old copies as mss. 5, 8, 2005, 2007, 2030, 4025 and YL2 for DrYt. <em>-aēm</em> well-attested in Pahlavi Yasna copies.
                Indian liturgial mss. <em>-əm</em>. Sanskrit Yasna also, but <em>-aēm</em> in Y14.3, ms. 677. <em>-īm</em> as a secondary evolution <em>-aēm</em>; <em>-īm</em> more likely as the opposite.
                Vid. <bibl>Kuiper, 1942</bibl>, p. 65 considers it a graphical variant; 
                <bibl>Tremblay, 2003</bibl>, pp. 248 ff. an authentic hysterodynamic from a different stem than <em>sāuuaŋhə̄e</em> (Y1.3): <em>sāuuaŋhi-</em> as noun (dat. <em>sāuuaŋhə̄e</em>), <em>sāuuaŋhay-</em> as a derivative of the first (acc. <em>sāuuaŋhaēm</em>).
                Either an old variant in the recitation, or an actual hysterodynamic, the mss. support the ending <em>-aēm</em>.
            </ab>
        </Commentary>
    </Apparatus>
